    <h1>Large Table Transformation in an OLTP Environment</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p>Let=E2=80=99s say we desire to apply a transformation to a large=
 table. Under normal circumstances, such an operation may take many hours a=
nd cause significant blocking and customer downtime. Examples of such trans=
formations include adding a new non-nullable column, changing a primary key=
, or otherwise updating every single row in the table, etc. Through a combi=
nation of tables, a view, and triggers, it is possible to accomplish operat=
ions like this with almost no downtime.</p>
<p></p>
<p>The idea is to create a new, empty table with the desired schema. The ex=
isting table will be renamed and a view created with the same name as the o=
riginal table. The view will query data from both the existing and new tabl=
es. This will allow existing consumers of the data to continue with busines=
s as usual with no changes and (almost) no downtime. Triggers (which will c=
ontain the transformation logic) will be created to intercept DML operation=
s on the table and dispatch them like this:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Inserts will be applied only to the new table</p></li>
<li>
<p>Deletes will be applied to both the current and new tables</p></li>
<li>
<p>Updates will occur on the new table where the rows already exist there. =
Rows in the current table will be moved.</p></li>
</ul>
<p></p>
<p>Once the setup is completed, a job can be started to transform existing =
rows in batches with a short delay between each batch. This job can be tune=
d as to batch size and time of day it is run in order to complete the trans=
formation is quickly as feasible without impacting operations. Depending on=
 the sensitivity of operations to these updates, it may be best to only run=
 this during off-hours. There is no single answer as to the best batch size=
, delay, or time of day. It is best to tune with some testing in a non-prod=
uction environment, but also design the job in such a way that it can be co=
nfigured in real-time with regards to batch size, delay, and hours of opera=
tion.</p>
<p></p>
<p>Note that while it is possible to leave this setup in place indefinitely=
 and let it completely transform organically, I would highly caution agains=
t such an approach. Eventually other schema changes will be needed on the t=
able. It becomes complicated to incorporate this next generation of changes=
 into this setup. Get the data transformed as quickly as feasible and tear =
this down.</p>
<p></p>
<p>Setup</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: sql; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">-- This =
is the original, existing "big" table
CREATE TABLE [dbo].[BigTable]
(
=09[BigTableID]=09INT IDENTITY(1, 1)=09NOT NULL,
=09[Column1]=09=09VARCHAR(20)=09=09=09NOT NULL,=09
=09[Column2]=09=09VARCHAR(20)=09=09=09NOT NULL,
=09CONSTRAINT [PK_BigTable] PRIMARY KEY CLUSTERED ([BigTableID])
);


-- We desire to add a new column non-nullable column (NewColumn) to the tab=
le.
-- We will add it to a new table and transform the data from the old table =
to the new table over a period of time.
-- In steps below, we create a view and triggers to completely insulate thi=
s change from the application while we migrate the data.
-- This is done with almost no downtime.
CREATE TABLE [dbo].[BigTable_new]
(
=09[BigTableID]=09INT IDENTITY(1, 1)=09NOT NULL,
=09[Column1]=09=09VARCHAR(20)=09=09=09NOT NULL,=09
=09[Column2]=09=09VARCHAR(20)=09=09=09NOT NULL,
=09[NewColumn]=09VARCHAR(20)=09=09=09=09NOT NULL,
=09CONSTRAINT [PK_BigTable_new] PRIMARY KEY CLUSTERED ([BigTableID])

);

-- Rename the existing table. After this operation and until the 3 views be=
low are created, inserts, updates, and deletes will fail.
-- The good news is that this is a sub-second operation. As an alternative,=
 we could place a lock on the table before these next 4 steps and
-- then release it after. That would cause any operations to be blocked (be=
 slightly slower from their point of view) vs. a hard failure.
EXECUTE sp_rename 'dbo.BigTable', 'BigTable_old';


-- This view will take on the desired table name so that no existing code n=
eeds to change. It will union together the data from the old and new tables=
.
CREATE VIEW [dbo].[BigTable]
AS

SELECT
=09[BigTableID],
=09[Column1],
=09[Column2],
=09NULL AS NewColumn
FROM
=09[dbo].[BigTable_old]

UNION ALL

SELECT
=09[BigTableID],
=09[Column1],
=09[Column2],
=09[NewColumn]
FROM
=09[dbo].[BigTable_new];


-- This trigger will ensure that all inserts occur to the new table
CREATE TRIGGER [dbo].[tri_BigTable] ON [dbo].[BigTable]
INSTEAD OF INSERT
AS
BEGIN

=09INSERT INTO [dbo].[BigTable_new]
=09(
=09=09[Column1],
=09=09[Column2],
=09=09[NewColumn]
=09)
=09SELECT
=09=09[Column1],
=09=09[Column2],
=09=09[NewColumn]
=09FROM Inserted;

END;


-- This trigger will trying deleting rows from both tables
CREATE TRIGGER [dbo].[trd_BigTable] ON [dbo].[BigTable]
INSTEAD OF DELETE
AS
BEGIN


=09DELETE bto
=09FROM [dbo].[BigTable_old] bto
=09=09INNER JOIN Inserted i ON [bto].[BigTableID] =3D [i].[BigTableID];

=09DELETE btn
=09FROM [dbo].[BigTable_new] btn
=09=09INNER JOIN Inserted i ON [btn].[BigTableID] =3D [i].[BigTableID];

END;


-- This trigger moves rows from the old table to the new as it updates or s=
imply updates the row in place if they are already in the new table
CREATE TRIGGER [dbo].[tru_BigTable] ON [dbo].[BigTable]
INSTEAD OF UPDATE
AS
BEGIN

=09BEGIN TRANSACTION

=09-- Update rows that are already in the new table
=09UPDATE dtn
=09SET
=09=09[dtn].Column1 =3D [i].[Column1],
=09=09[dtn].[Column2] =3D [i].[Column2],
=09=09[dtn].[NewColumn] =3D [i].[NewColumn]
=09FROM [dbo].[BigTable_new] dtn
=09=09INNER JOIN Inserted i on [dtn].[BigTableID] =3D [i].[BigTableID];

=09-- Insert rows into the new table that are in the old table
=09INSERT INTO [dbo].[BigTable_new]
=09(
=09=09[Column1],
=09=09[Column2],
=09=09[NewColumn]
=09)
=09SELECT
=09=09[i].[Column1],
=09=09[i].[Column2],
=09=09'NewColumn Default Value'
=09FROM Inserted i
=09WHERE [i].[BigTableID] IN (SELECT 1 FROM [dbo].[BigTable_old] WHERE [Big=
TableID] =3D [i].[BigTableID]);

=09-- Delete rows from the old table
=09DELETE bto
=09FROM [dbo].[BigTable_old] bto
=09=09INNER JOIN Inserted i ON [bto].[BigTableID] =3D [i].[BigTableID];

=09COMMIT TRANSACTION

END;

/* Cleanup all objects
DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS [dbo].[tri_BigTable];
DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS [dbo].[tru_BigTable];
DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS [dbo].[trd_BigTable];
GO
DROP VIEW IF EXISTS [dbo].[BigTable];
GO
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS [dbo].[BigTable];
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS [dbo].[BigTable_old];
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS [dbo].[BigTable_new];
*/</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p></p>
<p>Teardown (to be done when the row count in BigTable_old is 0</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">-- Simi=
lar to the initial setup, inserts, updates, and deletes will fail after the=
 triggers are dropped and before the table rename has occured.
-- The good news is that this is a sub-second operation. As an alternative,=
 we could place a lock on the table before these next 4 steps and
-- then release it after. That would cause any operations to be blocked (be=
 slightly slower from their point of view) vs. a hard failure.
DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS [dbo].[tri_BigTable];
DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS [dbo].[tru_BigTable];
DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS [dbo].[trd_BigTable];
DROP VIEW IF EXISTS [dbo].[BigTable];
EXECUTE sp_rename 'dbo.BigTable_new', 'BigTable';
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS [dbo].[BigTable_old];</pre>
</div>
</div>
